docs.abstract: President Trump, who is not a reader, has used Twitter to plug a slew of Trump-friendly books with titles like “Why We Fight” and “The Russia Hoax.”

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump, a leader who is not exactly a man of letters — at least not beyond those on his CAPS LOCK keyboard — has been using his Twitter account to promote a slew of books that he regards as “incredible,” “terrific” and “great originals.”

headline.main: Trump’s Book Club: A President Who Doesn’t Read Promotes the Books That Promote Him

docs.abstract: Representative-elect Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, the rising liberal star, cited a figure that refers to nearly two decades of internal financial adjustments, not actual spending.
docs.snippet: Representative-elect Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, the rising liberal star, cited a figure that refers to nearly two decades of internal financial adjustments, not actual spending.
docs.lead_paragraph: Representative-elect Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, the New York Democrat who has become a darling of the progressive left, was quoting from an article in The Nation about “massive accounting fraud” committed by the Pentagon from 1998 to 2015. But her suggestion that the $21 trillion in military transactions could have “already” paid two-thirds the cost of a “Medicare for all” health care system goes beyond what the article reported — and is misleading.

headline.main: The Misleading Claim That $21 Trillion in Misspent Pentagon Funds Could Pay for ‘Medicare for All’
